  "eprint": {
    "title": "TN-IDS for Network Layer Attacks in RPL based IoT Systems",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Ambili K N",
        "email": "ambili_p180002cs@nitc",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Jimmy Jose",
        "email": "injimmy@nitc",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Routing protocol for Low power and lossy network (RPL) is a standardized optimal protocol\nfor routing in Internet of Things (IoT). The constrained wireless sensor network in IoT is\ncharacterized by lack of processing speed, low power and low memory. Sometimes various\nnetwork attacks enabling the RPL network affect the network performance dismally. This leads\nto drastic variation in energy consumption at nodes and disturb the RPL network protocol\nstructure. This leads to reduced processing speed and memory allocation in the network. We\nfirst illustrate the attacks and their impact in RPL network by simulation. To detect such\nattacks, we propose an Intrusion Detection System (IDS) scheme for RPL network based on\ntrust computation. Trust based Neighbor notification IDS (TN-IDS) is a secure hierarchical\ndistribution system which monitors the network intrusion and checks the performance of the\nnetwork. The new TN-IDS system will track all nodes in the network and identify the malicious\nnodes. The activity list prepared by IDS indicates them to a sink node. This is achieved by\nintroducing a distributed leader election algorithm to collect metrics related to the RPL network.\nHence, the performance metrics of the RPL network together with TN-IDS module can identify\nthe malicious node and isolate them.",
    "keywords": [
      "IoT",
      "RPL",
      "DoS",
      "blackhole",
      "Topology attacks",
      "sinkhole",
      "IDS",
      "wormhole"
    ],
